y tied back to ionic bonding: the NaCl ionic lattice is described as held together by ionic bonds (electrostatic attraction among ions), connecting micro-level ion formation to macro-level crystal structure. [Data: Entities (1434, 1411, 919, 771, 1410); Relationships (2091, 2028, 1106, 1107, 1615)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"The NaCl ionic lattice is emphasized as a repeating 3D crystal arrangement with specific coordination details\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Beyond stating that NaCl forms an ionic lattice, the material specifies geometric/coordination features for the sodium chloride crystal lattice: each Cl− is surrounded by six Na+ ions and each Na+ is surrounded by six Cl− ions, highlighting the regular repeating arrangement typical of ionic crystals. [Data: Entities (1411, 919, 920, 921, 1434); Relationships (2028, 1106, 1107, 1614, 1615)]\\n\\nHands-on modeling (using clay/plastic balls) is included as an instructional method to help learners visualize this three-dimensional arrangement, showing that the community includes not only conceptual definitions but also pedagogy for building mental models of crystal lattices. [Data: Entities (1422, 1434, 771); Relationships (2046, 2066, 2091)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Physical properties and conductivity differences are used to distinguish ionic vs covalent substances\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Sodium chloride’s properties are described in ways typical for ionic lattices: high melting/boiling points and electrical non-conductivity in the solid state due to immobile ions, contrasted with conductivity when molten or in aqueous solution due to mobile ions. These statements are presented as part of the broader curriculum comparing ionic and covalent compounds. [Data: Entities (771, 190, 1495, 1170, 1449); Relationships (2201, 152)]\\n\\nA dedicated table (Table 10.5) is used to compare melting/boiling points and bonding classifications across examples, including ionic compounds (e.g., calcium oxide, potassium chloride) and covalent compounds (e.g., ethyl alcohol, sulphur dioxide). This anchors property comparisons in a standardized reference within the material. [Data: Entities (1495, 190, 1490, 1492, 1493); Relationships (2208, 2203, 2207, 2209, 2201)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Relative formula mass and empirical formula are positioned as key calculation concepts for ionic lattices\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Because ionic compounds are described as extended lattices rather than discrete molecules, the community emphasizes using relative formula mass (based on the empirical formula) instead of relative molecular mass. Sodium chloride is the worked example: its relative formula mass is computed as 23 + 35.5 = 58.5, and the molar mass is correspondingly 58.5 g mol−1. [Data: Entities (1170, 1172, 1171, 771, 1181); Relationships (1590, 1612, 1591)]\\n\\nThe material also includes practice-oriented components—such as a question set to compute molar masses of multiple compounds—indicating that the community includes both conceptual framing and calculation exercises. [Data: Entities (1212, 1213, 1214, 1216, 1218); Relationships (1695, 1697, 1700, 1698, 1691)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"NaCl is embedded in a broader set of example ionic compounds and polyatomic ions to generalize ionic-bonding rules\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The community broadens beyond NaCl by listing additional ionic compounds (e.g., lithium oxide, magnesium sulphide, calcium chloride, potassium fluoride) to generalize the idea that ionic compounds form via ionic bonding between cations and anions. These examples situate NaCl within a wider taxonomy of ionic substances. [Data: Entities (1170, 1416, 1417, 1418, 1419); Relationships (2031, 2032, 2033, 2034)]\\n\\nPolyatomic ions (ionic radicals) are introduced as charged groups of atoms that can form ionic compounds, with ammonium (NH4+), sulfate (SO4^2−), and nitrate (NO3−) used as examples; ammonium chloride and ammonium nitrate are specifically referenced as compounds containing the ammonium cation. This extends the bonding model beyond monoatomic ions like Na+ and Cl−. [Data: Entities (1412, 1413, 1414, 1415, 1420); Relationships (2035, 2036, 2037, 2039, 2041)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"A laboratory application thread connects chemical reagents (NaOH and CuSO4) to protein detection via a purple color change\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Separate from the ionic-lattice teaching thread, the community includes an applied lab procedure: the Biurete test for proteins. The relationships specify that sodium hydroxide and copper sulphate are used together as reagents, and that a purple colour change indicates a positive result for proteins. [Data: Entities (349, 369, 352, 397); Relationships (356, 354, 384)]\\n\\nCopper sulphate is referenced in two contexts—solution reagent in the Biurete test and anhydrous copper sulphate as a water indicator—indicating that the same compound appears across different classroom applications. [Data: Entities (352); Relationships (416, 356)]\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Seawater provides real-world context: sodium occurs naturally as dissolved salts such as NaCl\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The community links textbook concepts to nature by citing seawater as an aqueous environment containing sodium and magnesium as dissolved chloride salts, using sodium chloride as the primary example of sodium’s natural occurrence in compound form rather than as a native metal. Sodium chloride is explicitly noted as occurring in seawater. [Data: Entities (770, 771); Relationships (901, 922)]\\n\\nThis contextualization reinforces the conceptual claim that highly reactive metals like sodium are commonly found as compounds; here the dataset grounds that point specifically through the seawater–NaCl relationship and the seawater description that emphasizes dissolved salts. [Data: Entities (770, 771); Relationships (901, 922)]\"\n    }\n  ],\n